  "doc_id": "59557",
  "text": "While few studies have directly examined the role of mTORC1 signaling in RBCs, there is some evidence that dysregulation of protein translation downstream of mTORC1 may play a role in the development of anemia. The hereditary anemias, Diamond-Blackfan and 5q-syndrome, are caused by haploinsufficiency of ribosomal proteins S14 and S19, and recent data show that these anemias can be ameliorated by pharmacologic doses of L-leucine [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] , which activates mTORC1 signaling through S6K and promotes translation. Thus, our finding that RBCs depend critically on signaling through the mTORC1 pathway is consistent with the broader view that RBCs are uniquely sensitive to perturbations that affect protein translation.",
